{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"This is a cross-module handoff check (filesystem discovery/parsing/sorting -> runner execution order). The behavior text is about A→B ordering, not a single pure function. I rejected System because the behavior does not require real OS/network/subprocess effects beyond local wiring, and it does not require external contract validation.","test_description":"Create a test migrations directory with out-of-order filenames (e.g., 001, 010, 002), run the runner end-to-end in-process with a test DB/repo adapter, and assert applied order in recorded metadata is 001, 002, 010.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"This is persistence/readback coupling across runs (runner state + _migrations table), which is beyond unit logic and needs module interaction. I considered System but rejected it because the behavior text does not explicitly require real network/subprocess conditions; the idempotency invariant can be validated with integrated components and DB readback in test scope.","test_description":"Run runner once with a migration that creates a marker table/row, run runner again, then assert the migration appears once in _migrations and the side-effect appears only once (no duplicate DDL/DML effect).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.36,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted